    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "8f6a8ca6_b47e7858",
        "filename": "org.eclipse.jgit/src/org/eclipse/jgit/transport/forwarder/RouteResponse.java",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 28,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000671
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-05-19T22:34:38Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I think that\u0027s not a problem since there is no release yet which includes `RouteResponse` which was introduced after the last release 7.6.0. The [next JGit release is 7.7.0](https://projects.eclipse.org/projects/technology.jgit/governance) which is planned to be released on June 10 following the [release schedule of Eclipse IDE](https://github.com/eclipse-simrel/.github/blob/main/wiki/Simultaneous_Release.md).\n\nI think applications using a JGit version newer than the latest release (like Gerrit) have to accept the risk that new API introduced after the last release may be unstable and still change (or even be removed) until it\u0027s shipped in the next release.\n\n**Service releases** should only fix bugs.\n\n**Minor releases** can add new API or change existing API if the changes don\u0027t break API published in earlier releases.\n\n**Major releases** can break API published in earlier releases, the next one is 8.0.0. Breaking changes can be prepared on the `next` branch while we still prepease the next minor release on the `master` branch. We will merge the `next` branch into the `master` branch if we decide that the next release will bump the major version.",
      "parentUuid": "29cfff78_ce54611a",
      "revId": "542ba5a8413a7c39015684705724a41d638c1667",
      "serverId": "d5d70762-12d0-45a1-890d-524b12d3f735"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "f51eb96f_0cc11e68",
        "filename": "org.eclipse.jgit/src/org/eclipse/jgit/transport/forwarder/RouteResponse.java",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 28,
      "author": {
        "id": 1038403
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-05-19T22:55:00Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Thanks Matthias. Hopefully we don\u0027t need to evolve this quicker than what this allows, but I am worried that it might still. Would it make sense for us to move some classes where they are not part of the public API during the early phases, and to promote those later to the public API? If so, would that mean putting the classes in the \"internal\" packages?",
      "parentUuid": "8f6a8ca6_b47e7858",
      "revId": "542ba5a8413a7c39015684705724a41d638c1667",
      "serverId": "d5d70762-12d0-45a1-890d-524b12d3f735"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "9cf7dc72_7121e80a",
        "filename": "org.eclipse.jgit/src/org/eclipse/jgit/transport/forwarder/RouteResponse.java",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 28,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000671
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-05-19T23:11:42Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "yes, classes in internal packages are considered internal API and internal APIs can break between minor releases. That\u0027s a common convention in projects contributing to Eclipse IDE. That\u0027s why we export such packages in `MANIFEST.MF` as `x-internal:\u003dtrue` which ensures that OSGi bundles trying to import such a package get a warning stating that consuming internal API is discouraged.\n\nIf you think we should mark such API as experimental we could choose a package name containing a segment `experimental` e.g. `org.eclipse.transport.experimental.forwarder` and also mark it `x-internal` in `MANIFEST.MF`.",
      "parentUuid": "f51eb96f_0cc11e68",
      "revId": "542ba5a8413a7c39015684705724a41d638c1667",
      "serverId": "d5d70762-12d0-45a1-890d-524b12d3f735"
    },
